Let x be the number of dimes he has and y be the number of nickels. Since one dime is worth 10 cents and one nickel is worth 5 cents, x and y must satisfy the following system of equations:
\begin{align*}
x+y&=36\\
10x+5y&=\text{310 cents}
\end{align*}

Multiplying the first equation by 10 and subtracting it from the second equation, we get $5y=310-360$, so $y=5$.  Substituting into the first equation, we get $x=36-5=31$.  So Steve has $\boxed{31}$ dimes. The answer is 31

Let $a$ be the number of units of whole wheat flour and $b$ be the number of units of whole milk. We can make the following system of equations:

\begin{align*}
a+b&=n\\
13.6a+3.4b&=75\\
2.5a+3.7b&=15
\end{align*}

where $n$ is the number of units of dough. Notice that we can divide the second equation by 13.6 and the third equation by 2.5 to obtain a system of equations in the variables $a$ and $b$:

\begin{align*}
a+b&=n\\
1+0.25b&=75/13.6\\
0.5+0.7b&=75/25
\end{align*}

Solving this system, we find $a=5$ and $b=10$. So, $n=a+b=5+10=\boxed{15}$. The answer is 15

Let $\ell$ be the amount of 20% acid needed and $m$ be the amount of 60% acid needed.  Then, we can set up the following equations:

\begin{align*}
\ell + m &= 80 \text{ square-centimeters} \\
0.20 \ell + 0.60 m &= 0.45 (80) \\
\ell + m &= 80 \\
0.20 \ell + 0.60 m &= 36 \\
0.40 \ell &= 12 \\
\ell &= 30 \text{ square-centimeters}
\end{align*}

Therefore, $30$ square-centimeters of 20% acid and $50$ square-centimeters of 60% acid is needed to produce $80$ square-centimeters of a solution that is 45% pure acid.  The answer is 30

